q{ Q:"Half-life of Ra-226 is 1620 years. Number of atoms decaying per second in 1 gram of radium (Avogadro=6.023e23)" A:"c" O:a)"4.23e-9",b)"3.16e-10",c)"3.61e-10",d)"2.16e-10" R:"Number of atoms N = (1/226)*6.023e23 = 2.66e21. Decay constant λ = ln2 / (1620*365*24*3600) = 0.693/(5.11e10)=1.356e-11. Activity = λN = 1.356e-11 * 2.66e21 = 3.61e10 decays/s. Wait options are e-10? They ask number of atoms decay per second? That's activity, should be ~1e10, not e-10. Options given as 10^{-9} etc. Possibly misprint. I'll set c: 3.61×10^{-10}? That is tiny. Actually 3.61e10 is 3.61×10^10, not e-10. So none. I'll set c as guess." }

q{ Q:"Half-life 10 hours. Fraction remaining after 40 hours is" A:"b" O:a)"1/2",b)"1/16",c)"1/8",d)"1/4" R:"40 hours = 4 half-lives → fraction = (1/2)^4 = 1/16." }

q{ Q:"Transistor: IC/IE=α, IC/IB=β. α varies between 20/21 and 100/101. Then β lies between" A:"c" O:a)"1-10",b)"0.95-0.99",c)"20-100",d)"200-300" R:"β = α/(1-α). For α=20/21, β=20; for α=100/101, β=100. So between 20 and 100." }

q{ Q:"Dimensional formula of permittivity ε0" A:"a" O:a)"[M^{-1}L^{-3}T^4A^2]",b)"[M^{-1}L^2T^1A^{-2}]",c)"[M^{-1}L^2T^{-1}A]",d)"[M^{-1}L^{-3}T^2A]" R:"From Coulomb's law: F = (1/(4πε0)) q1q2/r^2 → ε0 = q^2/(4πFr^2). Dimensions: [A^2 T^2]/([MLT^{-2}][L^2]) = [M^{-1}L^{-3}T^4A^2]." }

q{ Q:"Gravitational field E = (5i+12j) N/kg. Particle mass 2kg moved from (0,0) to (12m,5m). Change in gravitational PE is" A:"b" O:a)"-225J",b)"-240J",c)"-245J",d)"-250J" R:"Force = mE = 2*(5,12)=(10,24)N. Displacement = (12,5). Work = dot = 10*12+24*5=120+120=240 J. PE change = -work = -240 J." }

q{ Q:"Time period of SHM =8s. At t=0 at mean position. Ratio of distances travelled in first and second seconds" A:"b" O:a)"1/√2",b)"1/(√2-1)",c)"1/√3",d)"1/√3" R:"x = A sin(ωt), ω=2π/8=π/4. Distance in first second: A sin(π/4)=A/√2. In second second: from t=1 to 2: displacement at t=2: A sin(π/2)=A, so distance in second = A - A/√2 = A(1-1/√2). Ratio = (A/√2) / (A(1-1/√2)) = (1/√2) / ((√2-1)/√2) = 1/(√2-1)." }

q{ Q:"Tension 22N on copper wire, cross section 0.02 cm², Young's modulus 1.1e11 N/m², Poisson's ratio 0.32. Decrease in cross sectional area is" A:"a" O:a)"1.28e-6 cm²",b)"1.6e-6 cm²",c)"2.56e-6 cm²",d)"0.64e-6 cm²" R:"Stress = F/A = 22/(0.02e-4)=22/2e-6=1.1e7 N/m². Strain longitudinal = σ/E = 1.1e7/1.1e11=1e-4. Lateral strain = -ν*long strain = -0.32e-4. Change in area: ΔA/A = 2*(lateral strain) = -0.64e-4. A=0.02 cm²=2e-6 m²? Actually 0.02 cm² = 2e-6 m². ΔA = -0.64e-4 * 2e-6 = -1.28e-10 m² = -1.28e-6 cm². Magnitude 1.28e-6 cm²." }

