q{ Q:"Pipe internal diameter D to another pipe of same size, water flows through n holes each diameter d. Speed in first pipe V, speed of water leaving second pipe is" A:"c" O:a)"D²V/(nd²)",b)"nD²V/d²",c)"nd²V/D²",d)"d²V/(nD²)" R:"Continuity: area1*V = n*area_hole*v → (πD²/4)V = n(πd²/4)v → v = (D²/(n d²))V. That is a. But option a is D²V/(nd²). Yes a. However c has nd²V/D² which is inverse. So a." }

q{ Q:"Liquid heated in copper vessel: apparent expansion coefficient 6e-6/C; in steel vessel: 24e-6/C. Linear expansion of copper 18e-6/C. Linear expansion of steel is?" A:"?" O:a)"",b)"",c)"",d)"" R:"Apparent expansion = real expansion of liquid - expansion of vessel (volumetric). For copper: γ_l - 3α_cu = 6e-6; for steel: γ_l - 3α_st = 24e-6. Subtract: 3α_st - 3α_cu = 18e-6 → α_st - α_cu = 6e-6 → α_st = 18e-6+6e-6=24e-6 /C. So answer 24e-6." }

q{ Q:"Temperature increases from T to T+ΔT, moment of inertia increases from I to I+ΔI. α is linear expansion coefficient. Then ΔI/I =" A:"b" O:a)"α ΔT",b)"2α ΔT",c)"ΔT/α",d)"2α/ΔT" R:"I ∝ (length)^2, so fractional change = 2α ΔT." }

q{ Q:"Work done to increase temperature of 1 mole ideal gas by 30°C, expanding under condition V ∝ T^{2/3}. R=8.314 J/mol/K" A:"c" O:a)"116.2J",b)"136.2J",c)"166.2J",d)"186.2J" R:"Given V = k T^{2/3}. Then PV = nRT → P = nRT/V = nRT/(k T^{2/3}) ∝ T^{1/3}. Work = ∫ P dV. dV = k*(2/3)T^{-1/3} dT. So dW = P dV = (constant * T^{1/3}) * (k*(2/3)T^{-1/3}) dT = (2/3) nR dT. So W = (2/3)nR ΔT = (2/3)*1*8.314*30 = (2/3)*249.42 = 166.28 J." }

q{ Q:"Power radiated by black body at T1 is P, max wavelength λ1. Temperature changed to T2, max wavelength λ1/2. Power radiated at T2 is" A:"c" O:a)"2P",b)"4P",c)"8P",d)"16P" R:"Wien's law: λ_max T = constant, so T2 = 2T1. Stefan-Boltzmann: P ∝ T^4, so P2 = (2^4)P = 16P. Option d is 16P. But options: a2P,b4P,c8P,d16P. So d." }

