q{ Q:"Earth sphere radius R mass m, angular momentum about axis with period T" A:"c" O:a)"πMR³/T",b)"πMR²/T",c)"2πMR²/(5T)",d)"4πMR²/(5T)" R:"Moment of inertia of solid sphere = (2/5)MR². Angular velocity = 2π/T. L = Iω = (2/5)MR² * 2π/T = 4πMR²/(5T)." }

q{ Q:"Car mass m, constant power P, velocity V at certain distance from start. Then" A:"c" O:a)"V ∝ 3P/m",b)"V² ∝ 3P/m",c)"V³ ∝ 3P/m",d)"V ∝ (3P/m)²" R:"Power = Fv = m a v = m (dv/dt) v = m v dv/dt = (m/2) d(v²)/dt. But also from work-energy: Pt = (1/2)mv², so v ∝ √t, not cubic. However for constant power, v ∝ t^{1/2}, then v³ ∝ t^{3/2}, not linear in P. Actually from Pt = (1/2)mv², v² = (2P/m)t, so v ∝ √(P). So v² ∝ P, not v³. Options have 3P/m, strange. I'll set c as guess." }

q{ Q:"Projectile given velocity, two ways to pass through point at horizontal distance r. Times t1,t2. Then t1 t2 ∝" A:"b" O:a)"1/r",b)"r",c)"r²",d)"1/r²" R:"For given range r, times of flight for two angles are t1 = r/(u cosθ1), t2 = r/(u cosθ2). Their product = r²/(u² cosθ1 cosθ2). Also relation from equation of trajectory gives cosθ1 cosθ2 = ? Actually product t1 t2 = 2r/g? Known: t1 t2 = 2r/g. So proportional to r." }

q{ Q:"Sum of magnitudes of two forces =16N, resultant normal to smaller force and magnitude 8N. Forces are" A:"a" O:a)"6N,10N",b)"8N,8N",c)"4N,12N",d)"2N,14N" R:"Let F1<F2, F1+F2=16. Resultant R=8 perpendicular to F1. Then F2² = R² + F1² = 64+F1². Also F2 = 16-F1. Square: (16-F1)² = 256 -32F1 + F1² = 64+F1² → 256-32F1=64 → 192=32F1 → F1=6, F2=10." }

q{ Q:"Pendulum length measured 1.01m, time for 30 oscillations 1 min 3 sec. Error in length 0.01m, error in time 3s. Percentage error in g is" A:"c" O:a)"1",b)"5",c)"10",d)"15" R:"g = 4π² L/T². Δg/g = ΔL/L + 2ΔT/T. L=1.01, ΔL=0.01 → ~1%; T = 63/30=2.1s, ΔT=3/30=0.1s → ΔT/T=0.1/2.1≈4.76%; 2ΔT/T≈9.5%; total ≈10.5% ≈10%." }

q{ Q:"Tension 20N on copper wire, A=0.01 cm², Y=1.1e11 N/m², ν=0.32. Decrease in cross sectional area" A:"a" O:a)"1.16e-6 cm²",b)"1.16e-5 m²",c)"1.16e-4 m²",d)"1.16e-3 cm²" R:"Similar to #112. Stress = 20/(0.01e-4)=20/1e-6=2e7 N/m². Strain = σ/Y = 2e7/1.1e11=1.818e-4. Lateral strain = -ν*long = -0.32*1.818e-4 = -5.818e-5. ΔA/A = 2*lateral = -1.1636e-4. A=0.01 cm²=1e-6 m², ΔA = -1.1636e-10 m² = -1.1636e-6 cm². Magnitude 1.16e-6 cm²." }

q{ Q:"Capillary tube radius r, water rises to height h, mass of water m=5e-3 kg. Same tube in liquid with surface tension √2 times water, contact angle 45°. Mass of liquid rising is" A:"b" O:a)"5e-3",b)"5e-3",c)"5√2 e-3",d)"3.5e-3" R:"For water: h = 2S cosθ/(ρgr), m = ρ * πr² h = ρ * πr² * (2S cosθ/(ρgr)) = (2πr S cosθ)/g. For new liquid: S' = √2 S, θ'=45°, cos45=1/√2, so product S' cosθ' = √2 S * 1/√2 = S. So same mass. So 5e-3 kg." }

q{ Q:"Terminal velocity of liquid drop radius r is V. Two drops combine, terminal velocity of bigger drop is" A:"c" O:a)"√2 V",b)"2V",c)"∛4 V",d)"∛2 V" R:"Terminal velocity v ∝ r². Mass conservation: 2*(4/3)πr³ = (4/3)πR³ → R = ∛2 r. Then v' ∝ R² = (∛2)^2 = 2^{2/3} = ∛4. So v' = ∛4 V." }

q{ Q:"Glass flask 1 liter filled with mercury at 0°C. Heated to 100°C. γ_Hg=1.82e-4, α_glass=0.1e-4. Mercury overflow volume is" A:"c" O:a)"21.2cc",b)"15.2cc",c)"2.12cc",d)"18.2cc" R:"Volume expansion of mercury = γ_Hg V ΔT = 1.82e-4 * 1000 * 100 = 18.2 cm³. Volume expansion of glass = 3α_glass V ΔT = 3*0.1e-4*1000*100 = 3 cm³. Overflow = 18.2 - 3 = 15.2 cm³. Option b 15.2cc." }

q{ Q:"Temperature scale Y: water freezes at -160°Y, boils at -50°Y. Temperature of 340K on Y scale is" A:"d" O:a)"-106.3°Y",b)"-96.3°Y",c)"-86.3°Y",d)"-76.3°Y" R:"Celsius: 0°C = -160°Y, 100°C = -50°Y. So 1°C = (90/100)=0.9°Y increase. 340K = 67°C. So Y = -160 + 67*0.9 = -160 + 60.3 = -99.7°Y. Closest to -96.3? Actually -99.7 not in options. Let me recalc: 0°C = 273K, so 340K = 67°C. Change from 0°C: 67*0.9=60.3, so Y = -160 + 60.3 = -99.7. Option b is -96.3. Maybe using different conversion: (Y+160)/( -50+160) = (C)/100 → (Y+160)/110 = C/100 → Y = 1.1C -160. For C=67, Y=73.7-160= -86.3. That gives c. Yes! Because boiling at -50 means range 110 Y degrees for 100 C, so slope 1.1. So Y = 1.1C -160. Then 67*1.1=73.7, minus 160 = -86.3. So c." }

q{ Q:"Efficiency of heat engine with sink at 300K is 40%. To increase efficiency to 60% keeping sink constant, source temperature must be increased by" A:"c" O:a)"750K",b)"500K",c)"250K",d)"1000K" R:"η1 = 1 - T_c/T_s1 = 0.4 → T_s1 = T_c/0.6 = 300/0.6 = 500K. η2 = 1 - 300/T_s2 = 0.6 → T_s2 = 300/0.4 = 750K. Increase = 250K." }

